Reference-contexts: This model is abstracted by the multicast group (M uG) concept. In order to implement a M uG most efficiently and not to compromise the ATM QoS, native ATM multicast facilities should be exploited. ATM facilitates multicast communication by providing a point-to-multipoint (ptmpt) connection type <ref> [3, 4] </ref>. This type of connection unidirectionally connects a single source ATM end-point (termed the root) to multiple destination ATM end-points (termed leaves). A M uG can be implemented using either a mesh of ptmpt connections or a multicast server. <p> In both of these techniques, it is necessary to know the identities of the end-points participating in the connection. This information (to which we refer in the rest of the paper as group membership information) is needed at connection set-up time. In the ATM Forum specification of UNI 4.0 <ref> [4] </ref> the question of how to obtain the identities of the ptmpt connection participants is left open, and the existence of some external directory service or other mechanism is assumed. However, the scaling of such a service to a WAN is not a trivial task.
